step.reason:
\text{There is a standard result } \\
\int e^x [\, f(x) + f'(x)\, ] dx = e^x f(x) + C \\
\text{The key is to identify what f(x) and f'(x) are.}

e^x  \left[ \dfrac{1}{x} - \dfrac{1}{x^2} \right] \text{ matches the form } \\
e^x [\, f(x) + f'(x)\, ] \text{ only if }f(x) = \dfrac{1}{x} \\
\text{Remember }\dfrac{d}{dx} \left[ \dfrac{-1}{x^2} \right] = 2 \dfrac{1}{x^3} \\
\text{ and thus, }
f(x) \neq - \dfrac{1}{x^2}
